(155, 1, '2017-04-16 02:39:56', '2017-04-16 02:39:56', '<h1>HOME SALMON</h1>\r\nBy Jingmei Zou\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe tides come and go, heeding the moon’s pull. Four years have passed since the salmon fry swam down to sea, four years since they departed from home, four years since they left fresh water for bitter brine. Now their blood sings to them, and it calls for them to return to their birthplace.\r\n\r\nThis is what it is like to be River, one salmon of many.\r\n\r\nThe mouth of the river, which she once swam through, gushes water maddeningly sweet, summoning those that once swam together as they headed to sea to come again to where they once parted. Before River are multitudes, all jostling to enter the fjords, driven by the urge to return. There is a scent that awakens memories. Home! Home! She remembers the waters of his birthplace, smells them in the sea. Home! Must return! Am returning!\r\n\r\nBut danger is upon her and her companions. Below, Charybdis lurks, salmon sharks ravenous for the taste of salmon. The sea lions are like the heads of Scylla, snatching their targets from the throng. But worse yet are the terrors from above. Like the avenging Erinyes of myth, they swoop from the air, and seize unsuspecting victims from the river full of fish. With sharp talons, the bald eagles hunt and guard the coast, the first trial of many for these salmon in their quest to return home.\r\n\r\nAfter they pass from ocean to river, they change. The maddening need to return home drives them. We all swim beneath Death’s shadow. They fast. There is no time to eat. They drink not. Can’t remember to, can’t feel thirst, must go back.\r\n\r\nThey all will serve and do their duty. Must go back to our birthplace.\r\n\r\nThe rivers only flow towards the sea. The same power that once helped them in their travels was now against them, for as they return home, they fight the rushing water, struggling upstream as the need to return drives them on, a berserker trance. Can’t feel pain, only need.\r\n\r\nAnother trial comes, even as they strive to go against the current. Gravity gives power to the rapids, and they become waterfalls. The salmon, as they travel towards home, now must leap up. But there is danger. Though like the Maenads of Bacchus they are in a frenzy, leaping forward and up, they are not protected from harm. Bones shatter, organs rupture, even as they desperately go forward and towards home. Yet another foe awaits. Upon the waterfall, a bear stands, waiting for an unfortunate soul. As River leaps, she makes a mistake. She goes too much to one side, too close to the bear. Its jaws snap closed. Must go on.\r\n\r\nRiver struggles. The bear shakes him. Her spine snaps. She cannot move. Couldn’t go on. Did all she could.\r\n\r\nShe is no more. Her flesh feeds another. A death feeds a life. It is an eternal cycle.\r\n\r\nOverhead, a crow passes through the air. Its shadow falls over River. We are all in Death’s shadow.\r\n\r\nBelow, the waterfall flowed downwards, and the river of salmon gleamed as they swam onwards to return home. Though some fell, the others went on. Homewards.\r\n\r\nThey morph. Know of their being male and female. Become different. The pull grows stronger.\r\n\r\nAnother salmon, which may be known as Brook, swims with the rest. He seeks to do its duty, he seeks to heed the call, he seeks to go home. Bruises hinder him not, nor the fear of death. Must go home.\r\n\r\nSunrise. Sunset. The moon waxed and waned. Still they went on. The water tasted familiar. Ravens circled. Bears fished their dead from the still ponds where they took refuge when the way was blocked due to draught. Time had no meaning. Time had no meaning. Need to return. It has meaning. They race against time, against their own weakening bodies. We swim beneath Death’s wings.\r\n\r\nNow wolves prowled on the banks of their home water. Bears waded and hunted in rivers teeming with fish. Others stood on the waterfall. With so many fish leaping, driven on by berserker madness, having care for naught but returning, many were caught in the mouths of the predators, but those that fell were but a drop in the sea of fish, all pouring into the waters where they themselves were hatched. They had not eaten, they had not had anything to drink. Battered, bruised, wounded. But they were home.\r\n\r\nBrook leapt with the rest, and landed upon the waters where he once was hatched. Where his parents once laid his egg. Where their parents had laid theirs. Of every thousand eggs of each generation, only four would return. He had succeeded. He now was above the same gravel in which he was hatched. He was one of the lucky four. Brook had returned home.\r\n\r\nYet as it oft was, it was at joy’s zenith that one’s nadir was ushered. Another bear lunged from above, and it was the fish that had no luck. His assailant, gorged upon the feast, took no more than a few choice bites from him afore tossing his still living body out onto the flowing water. With clouding eyes, Brook looked upon the skies above his birthwaters, in which white gulls circled. On either bank there was green, vibrant, clear, brilliant green. A beautiful emerald, so pure and unlike the algae and seaweed of the oceans. A color full of life, achingly soothing, comforting. Rest, it whispered, you are home. Trees rose to touch the heavens, and though there was death, there also was life. A crow flew overhead, mingling with the white-feathered gulls. Death was a certainty, but he had answered the call. He had come back, he now has done his duty. Time to rest now.\r\n\r\nHis body goes back to the earth from whence it came, feeding the trees that purified the water. The water which then gave him life, and would now give life to his kindred and his kindred’s kin. His essence now rises in those growths that created his home, to keep it so for the generations to come.\r\n\r\nThough all who swam upstream did so under the shadow of Death, they have done their duty. They swim in an eternal cycle. Life brings new life, and death breathes vitality into the world. Though death comes, nothing is ever doomed to oblivion. What once came to being here has now metamorphosed to give existence to another. Endless turnings of an eternal cycle, blazing in a hearth-fire of rose and green Northern Lights. They salmon are hatched, and leave home to grow, afore in the end returning, bringing some of the sea with them as they go home to rest.', 'Group II (10-12 years) 1st Prize Winner - Home salmon by Jingmei Zou', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'group-ii-10-12-years-1st-prize-winner-home-salmon-by-jingmei-zou', '', '', '2017-04-16 02:39:56', '2017-04-16 02:39:56', '', 0, 'http://drzhidao.com/littlestar/?page_id=155', 0, 'page', '', 0),
